stained close beneath it would alter the short-term picture materially.\n\nThe hourly read reinforces the neutral bias. Price pushed to the session high of 16.576 in the 09:00 candle before pulling back in an orderly fashion through the European morning. The H1 sequence from that high shows a series of lower highs and lower lows into the early afternoon, with price settling back toward the 16.514 area \u2014 broadly consistent with a mean-reversion towards the middle of the intraday range. There is no clear directional momentum on the hourly chart at present; rather, the pair appears to be digesting the overnight and early morning gains.\n\nThe economic calendar carries no scheduled events of note for today, which removes a potential catalyst for a sharp directional move. In the absence of data, price action is likely to remain technically driven, with liquidity conditions potentially thinner and moves more susceptible to positioning flows or broader emerging market sentiment shifts.\n\nWhat would change the read? A daily close above the 16.578 prior reaction zone, particularly on expanding range, would shift attention to the 16.618 area and introduce a tentatively more constructive short-term scenario for the dollar. Conversely, a decisive hourly close back beneath the 16.494 prior reaction zone would suggest the recovery from the July lows is losing conviction and bring the 16.382 support cluster back into focus. Until either boundary is resolved on a closing basis, the neutral framing holds.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}